#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:245
msgid "Selected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:241
msgid ""
"This will delete the selected control points, *without* breaking the curve "
"(i.e. the adjacent points will be directly linked, joined, once the "
"intermediary ones are deleted). Remember that NURBS order cannot be higher "
"than its number of control points, so it might decrease when you delete some "
"control point. Of course, when only one point remains, there is no more "
"visible curve, and when all points are deleted, the curve itself is deleted."
msgstr ""
"Ceci va supprimer les points de contrôle sélectionnés, *sans* casser la "
"courbe (càd les points adjacents seront directement liés, joints, une fois "
"les points intermédiaires supprimés). Rappelez-vous que l'ordre de NURBS ne "
"peut être supérieur à son nombre de points de contrôle, ainsi il peut "
"diminuer si vous supprimez des points de contrôle. Bien sûr, quand un seul "
"point reste, il n'y a plus de courbe visible, et quand tous les points sont "
"supprimés, la courbe elle-même est supprimée. "

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:252
msgid "Segment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:248
msgid ""
"This option is somewhat the opposite to the preceding one, as it will cut "
"the curve, without removing any control points, by erasing one selected "
"segment. This option always removes *only one* segment (the last \"selected"
"\" one), even when several are in the selection. So to delete all segments "
"in your selection, you will have to repetitively use the same erase option..."
msgstr ""
"Cette option est en quelque sorte le contraire de la précédente, car elle va "
"couper la courbe, sans supprimer de tout point de contrôle, en effaçant un "
"segment sélectionné. Cette option supprime toujours *seulement un* segment "
"(le dernier \"sélectionné\"), même quand plusieurs figurent dans la "
"sélection. Ainsi pour supprimer tous les segments dans votre sélection, vous "
"devrez utiliser itérativement la même option,,,"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:259
msgid "Deleting Curve Selected."
msgstr "Suppression de la courbe sélectionnée."

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:264
msgid "Deleting Curve segments."
msgstr "Suppression de segments de la courbe"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:270
msgid "Opening and Closing a Curve"
msgstr "Ouverture et fermeture de courbe."

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid "Menu:     :menuselection:`Curve --> Toggle Cyclic`"
msgstr "Menu :     :menuselection:`Curve --> Toggle Cyclic`"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid "Hotkey:   :kbd:`Alt-C`"
msgstr "Raccourci :   :kbd:`Alt-C`"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:280
msgid ""
"This toggles between an open curve and closed curve (Cyclic). Only curves "
"with at least one selected control point will be closed/open. The shape of "
"the closing segment is based on the start and end handles for Bézier curves, "
"and as usual on adjacent control points for NURBS. The only time a handle is "
"adjusted after closing is if the handle is an *Auto* one. Fig. :ref:`fig-"
"curves-editing-open-close` is the same Bézier curve open and closed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:287
msgid ""
"This action only works on the original starting control-point or the last "
"control-point added. Deleting a segment(s) does not change how the action "
"applies; it still operates only on the starting and last control-points. "
"This means that :kbd:`Alt-C` may actually join two curves instead of closing "
"a single curve! Remember that when a 2D curve is closed, it creates a "
"renderable flat face."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:297
msgid "Open and Closed curves."
msgstr "Courbes ouvertes et fermées."

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:303
msgid "Switch Direction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid ""
"Menu:     :menuselection:`Curve --> Segments --> Switch Direction`, :"
"menuselection:`Specials --> Switch Direction`"
msgstr ""
"Menu :     :menuselection:`Curve --> Segments --> Switch Direction`, :"
"menuselection:`Specials --> Switch Direction`"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid "Hotkey:   :kbd:`W-Numpad2`"
msgstr "Raccourci :   :kbd:`W-Numpad2`"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:314
msgid ""
"This command will \"reverse\" the direction of any curve with at least one "
"selected element (i.e. the start point will become the end one, and *vice "
"versa*). This is mainly useful when using a curve as path, or using the "
"bevel and taper options."
msgstr ""
"Cette commande va \"inverser\" la direction de toute courbe avec au moins un "
"élément sélectionné (càd. le point de début va devenir le point de fin, et "
"*vice versa*). C'est utile principalement dans l'utilisation d'une courbe "
"comme chemin, ou l'utilisation des options *bevel* et *taper*. "

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:320
msgid "Converting Tools"
msgstr "Outils de conversion"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:323
msgid "Converting Curve Type"
msgstr "Conversion de type de courbe"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid "Panel:    Curve Tools --> Set Spline type"
msgstr "Panneau :    Curve Tools --> Set Spline type"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:334
msgid "Set Spline Type button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:337
msgid ""
"You can convert splines in a curve object between Bézier, NURBS, and Poly "
"curves. Press :kbd:`T` to bring up the Tool Shelf. Clicking on the *Set "
"Spline Type* button will allow you to select the Spline type (Poly, Bézier "
"or NURBS)."
msgstr ""
"Vous pouvez convertir des splines en un objet Courbe entre Bézier, NURBS, et "
"Poly Courbe. Pressez :kbd:`T` pour accéder au Tool Shelf. Le clic sur le "
"bouton *Set Spline Type* vous permettra de sélectionner le type de Spline "
"(Poly, Bézier or NURBS)."

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:341
msgid ""
"Note, this is not a \"smart\" conversion, i.e. Blender does not try to keep "
"the same shape, nor the same number of control points. For example, when "
"converting a NURBS to a Bézier, each group of three NURBS control points "
"become a unique Bézier one (center point and two handles)."
msgstr ""
"Notez que ce n'est par une conversion \"intelligente\", càd. que Blender ne "
"cherche ni à garder la même forme, ni le même nombre de points de contrôle. "
"Par exemple, la conversion d'un NURBS en Bézier, chaque groupe de trois "
"points de contrôle NURBS devient un unique point Bézier (un point central et "
"deux poignées)"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:347
msgid "Convert Curve to Mesh"
msgstr "Conversion de courbe en maillage"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid "Mode:     Object Mode"
msgstr "Mode :     Mode Object"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst
msgid ""
"Menu:     :menuselection:`Object --> Convert to --> Mesh From Curve/Meta/"
"Surface/Text`"
msgstr ""
"Menu :     :menuselection:`Object --> Convert to --> Mesh From Curve/Meta/"
"Surface/Text`"

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:357
msgid ""
"There is also an \"external\" conversion, from curve to mesh, that only "
"works in *Object Mode*. It transforms a *Curve* object into a *Mesh* object, "
"using the curve resolution to create edges and vertices. Note that it also "
"keeps the faces and volumes created by closed and extruded curves."
msgstr ""
"Il y a une conversion \"externe\", de courbe en maillage, qui fonctionne "
"uniquement en *Mode Object*. Elle transforme un objet *Courbe* en un objet "
"*Maillage*, en utilisant la résolution de la courbe pour créer des arêtes et "
"des sommets. Notez qu'elle garde aussi les faces et volumes créés par les "
"courbes fermées et extrudées."

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing/introduction.rst:364
msgid "Convert Mesh to Curve"
msgstr "Conversion de maillage en courbe "

